 Norman bearer of this name, from Montfort-sur-Risle in Eure, near Brionne, accompanied William the Conqueror in his invasion of England in 1066. Simon <i>de Montfort</i>, 6th Earl of Leicester, led a rebellion against Henry III (1216–1272)."],"variants":[{"name":"Manford","meanings":["English (West Midlands; of Norman origin): variant of   Mountford  ."]},{"name":"Munford","meanings":["English (Norfolk): habitational name from Mundford in Norfolk, so named from the Old English personal name <i>Munda</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mountford  ."]},{"name":"Montford","meanings":["English (Shropshire): variant of   Mountford  ."]},{"name":"Mumford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Mountford  .","variant of   Munford  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Christopher ;  also of   Katherine   and its variants. In the medieval period it was a pet form of   Christian   and   Christiana ."],"variants":[{"name":"Christopher","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Katherine Mountford was born in 1325, in Norfolk, England, her father, Sir Osbert Mountford Lord Of Mountford, was 23 and her mother, Lady Mary Jean Stapleton, was 23. She married Richard Fitzgilbert Beaupre in 1324, in Wellingham, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1373, in Outwell, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1325–1373":"1325–1373","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1348–1396":"1348–1396","1303–1396":"1303–1396","1302–1355":"1302–1355","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1303":"1303","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1396":"1396","1373":"1373","1328":"1328","Outwell, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Outwell, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Outwell, Norfolk, England":"Outwell, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1325–1373":"1325–1373","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1348–1396":"1348–1396","1303–1396":"1303–1396","1302–1355":"1302–1355","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1303":"1303","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1396":"1396","1373":"1373","1328":"1328","Outwell, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Outwell, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Outwell, Norfolk, England":"Outwell, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1325–1373":"1325–1373","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1348–1396":"1348–1396","1303–1396":"1303–1396","1302–1355":"1302–1355","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1303":"1303","1302":"1302","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1396":"1396","1373":"1373","1328":"1328","Outwell, Norfolk, England, United